# User Management with System CLI

In the system, CLI commands are used to list users and groups, set and reset user passwords, and lock and unlock user accounts.
The system administrator can also manage lock threshold, lock time, and authenticate lock parameters using CLI commands.

The following table provides the user names, generic permissions, and corresponding login shell access for executing CLI commands.

### User-name and permissions

| User-name  | Generic permission |
| :--- | :---:| 
| sysread | Commands that perform read operations. No access to commands that change the current state or parameter of any object in the system. | 
| sysappladmin | Commands that have application-level access, but not system-level access. Commands that require system-level access are write operations for software management and state management, for which sysappladmin does not have access. |
